<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Select Committee Inquiry: Food Security</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> from the Department of Environment, Food and Rural Affairs</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This written evidence contains contributions from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the following </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Gov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ernment D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">epartments: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BIS, DfID, DH, DECC, DfT and HMT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Food security is a broad theme which encapsulates challenges to Governments and society over a wide range of topics.  It links to global agricultural production and markets, competitiveness, population growth, poverty, env</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ironmental impacts and technological developments. Activities across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment and internationally are trying to address these challenges. They are challenges that cannot be addressed by the UK alone, but rather by the UK as part of an international commu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nity. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The 2011 Government Office for Science’s Foresight Report, ‘The Future of Food and Farming’ explored the increasing pressures on the global food system between now and 2050, and asked how a future global population of 9 billion people can all be fed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> healthily and sustainably.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It stated that o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n the demand side, global population size will increase from nearly seven billion today to eight billion by 2030, and probably to over nine billion by 2050; many people are likely to be wealthier, creating demand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for a more varied, high-quality diet requiring additional resources to produce. On the production side, competition for land, water and energy will intensify</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Recent FAO projections state that globally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">demand for food is expected to increase by around 38</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">% by 2030 and by 60% by 2050</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Foresight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">identified factors increasing pressure on finite land and marine resources</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which include climate change, demographic shifts, changing patterns of work, and habitation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that wil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l create major challenges and intensify the demands we make on our land and seas. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Foresight report identified five key challenges to the future, which the Government has used to inform and shape actions to address food security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Balancing future deman</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d and supply sustainably</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ii.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ensuring adequate stability in food prices</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iii.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Achieving global access to food and ending hunger</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iv.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Managing the contribution of the food system to the mitigation of climate change</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">v.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Maintaining biodiversity and ecosystem services while fee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ding the world.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The report remains a significant part of the Government evidence and analysis base with regards to global and UK food security. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">UK food security – key messages </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The UK currently enjoys a high degree of food security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in terms of access,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> availability, resilience and variety of food supply.  This is built on both a strong food production base in the UK and access to a wide variety of markets through the EU and an open, rules-based world trading system. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK food security is supported by cons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">umer prosperity and income, which is addressed through the Government’s focus on growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The evidence for this is in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UK Food Security Assessment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, published in 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which analysed the different factors impacting on UK food supply.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> represents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">most current and complete analysis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the risks and challenges to UK food supply and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">places the UK’s food security within a global context.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">urther details and a summary can be found in Annex A.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2012 officials reassessed the report and concluded that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it still represents a robust analysis of food security in the UK.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While there are a number of working definitions of food security, the common elements of these definitions are the availability, access, affordability, safety and resilience of food. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK Food Security Assessment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">analysed the UK’s food security position across six themes relating to these elements – global availability, global resource sustainability, UK availability of access, UK food chain resilience, household food security, and sa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fety and confidence.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Each theme consists of a headline indicator, which captures a major or representative element of the theme, and several supporting indicators which explore related aspects of the theme. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2012, an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">internal analysis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of these indicators</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">concluded that the 2010 Assessment remained valid in the medium term but would be updated at 6-8 year intervals if warranted. This reflects the fact that many of the indicators in the assessment are relatively slow-moving or reflect structural issues whic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h do not tend to see significant changes over a short period of time.  However, some indicators have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">changed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> slightly since the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ssessment, for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, global resource sustainability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. But even taking these changes into account</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> given the wide range </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">factors </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that frame UK food security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the overall assessment remains very positive.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Overall, the Assessment concluded that the UK is well placed to deal with future challenges, though the Government continues to monitor the long-term trends that affect our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ability to continue to enjoy affordable, safe, nutritious and sustainable food. One clear message is that the UK’s food security depends on being able to source from a variety of stable countries, including domestic production: this diversity of supply enh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ances security by spreading risks, widening options and keeping prices competitive. Open markets and trade remain the best ways to enable the UK to stay resilient and food secure.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Framework</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The six themes of the UK Food Security Assessment -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">global availability, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">global reso</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">urce sustainability, UK availability of access, UK food chain resilience, household food security, and safety and confidence - reflect a number of underlying factors which are critical for thinking about the UK’s food securi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Global demand and supply position is critical: UK food prices and food supply primarily reflect global commodity markets.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The challenges identified by Foresight about balancing global demand and supply sustainably is based on projected demand growth fl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owing from a global population of 9 billion by 2050, coupled with increasing urbanisation and changes in diets. Projections in the supply side of the equation are more difficult: meeting this demand will require big improvements in global agricultural prod</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uctivity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Globally, there is enough food to feed the population at the moment – yet almost 1 billion people are estimated to be suffering hunger and malnutrition; so these issues are as much about income and poverty as about food production.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These factors </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">point to the importance of:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Measures which ensure that markets operate effectively to transmit price signals from rising demand, particularly measures to liberalise trade in food and agricultural products;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ii.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The importance of research and development aimed a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t raising agricultural productivity. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ood </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ecurity policy priorities</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have outlined the Government’s general approach to food security in detail below. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he key things </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> we are doing to ensure continued food security in the UK are:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Pursuing policie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s across Government to ensure continued economic growth and higher levels of income for all UK households;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Removing barriers to competiveness and enhancing the productivity of the agricultural and food sectors to help meet rising global demand;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Pressing fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r reform of agricultural and trade policies, such as the C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ommon </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gricultural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">olicy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which distort markets both at home and abroad;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ensuring that the UK food sector continues to foster healthy competition and delivers real benefits for UK consumers.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Before</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> addressing the eight issues on which the Committee has invited evidence, it may be helpful to set out the Government’s overall approach to the food sector.</span><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Government’s approach to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> sector</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="723" height="972" alt="" style="margin-left:-5.25pt; margin-top:-35.05pt; position:absolute; z-index:-65534" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government champions a thriving, competitive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British food and farming sector, driving sustainable growth in the wider rural economy in support of rural communities. The food chain has a key role to play in restoring growth to the economy – food and drink is the largest manufacturing sector in the UK,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the food chain as a whole accounts for 7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">% of national GVA, and 3 million jobs. Moreover, it is a sector that has continued to grow throughout the recent economic downturn.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government is supporting the food sector to continue to grow through a ra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nge of policies:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">short term </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Government is providing support to help the sector grow by, for example:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">taking advantage of expanding world demand for food through exports, by making food and drink a priority sector, and through negotiations with p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">articular countries to improve market access for UK food and drink products;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">funding WRAP to work with the food and drink sector to help them reduce food and packaging waste through initiatives such as the Courtauld Commitment and the Hospitality and Food </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Service Voluntary Agreement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">working with industry to remove any barriers to UK producers from making the most of opportunities to supply the UK market.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">longer term </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Government is providing strategic support to ensure the long term resilience of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the sector to provide the basis for sustainable growth into the future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">including ensuring a heal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">thy diet for the UK population, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">through a range of measures to build resilience and remove barriers to the sector’s success. These include,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for example:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ensur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing a robust and effective regulatory framework that gives confidence to consumers (in the UK and in export markets) about the quality of UK food and drink, by:</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 90pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">commissioning a fundamental external review of the integrity of the food chain to ensure we ide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntify any improvements to systems to restore confidence in the light of the horsemeat fraud;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 90pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">responding to consumer demands for better information through improved country of origin labelling of meat;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 90pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> giving confidence to build long term customer/supplier</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> relationships within the food chain by setting up the Grocery Code Adjudicator;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 90pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tripping out unnecessary rules to give the food industry freedom to innovate (e.g. simplifications of regulations defining jam and fruit juice).</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Working with industry to buil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d the food supply chain’s already strong resilience to shocks and events that can affect both short and long-term stability and growth;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A concerted effort to realise the economic potential of the UK’s world leading science and research base in agri-food th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rough the Agri-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ech Strategy, including new funding of £160m to bring together expertise in new centres to translate scientific know-how into tools and techniques that can be applied to raise the performance of the agriculture sector in the UK and to export to the world; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with industry (Agri-Tech Catalyst) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to commercialise new agri-technologies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="739" height="623" alt="" style="margin-left:-16.5pt; margin-top:-15pt; position:absolute; z-index:-65535" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Working with the Global Food Security programme and Leadership Council to join up and maximise impact of research and innovation delivered by government,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> research counc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ils and industry;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Supporting innovation and knowledge transfer to improve food production sustainably through T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">echnology </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">trategy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-led collaborative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">research and development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  and Defra’s new Sustainable Intensification Platform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suppor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ting the industry-led skills agenda to ensure that the sector has the skilled workforce it needs to thrive in the future;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Implementing reforms of the EU Common Agricultural Policy and Common Fisheries Policy in ways that remove barriers and provide maximum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> flexibility to UK producers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Supporting the agricultural sector and wider food industry in adapting to climate change through the Environment Agency Climate Ready support service and actions set out in the National Adaptation Programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Working with busin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ess through the Public Health Responsibility Deal to secure a food supply which helps </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e diet and population health.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Building resilience in a global context</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The policies highlighted above focus on what the Government can do within the UK to help the agri-food sectors be the best they can be to contribute to growth and take advantage of expanding world markets, but the UK cannot be seen in isolation. World mark</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ets in agricultural commodities and food products are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">key for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the UK food sector, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the UK needs to be prepared to meet a range of global challenges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in order to build the long term resilience of the sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The short and long-term challenges are interrel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ated: the food chain needs to be competitive and productive in order to continue to be able to deliver high quality, safe and sustainable food, while addressing the future challenges of global food security, climate change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">natural resource sustainabili</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the environmental impacts of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increased demand for food arising from global income and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">population</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">How best to improve UK (and EU) food security, including using resources more efficiently</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Key points</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As noted in the summary of the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Food Security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Ass</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">essment above, the UK currently enjoys a high degree of food security.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A key area of focus in ensuring that this remains the case is continuing to work to maintain and improve openness of world markets which underpins the diversity of the UK’s food supply, e.g. pressing for tariff reductions and other market opening measures,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">challenging</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inappropriate responses to food price spikes such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">export bans.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Another key area of focus is pressing for reform of restrictive EU policies to improve competitiveness, particularly the C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ommon </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gricultural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">olicy (CAP)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, but also the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ommon Fisheries Policy (CFP)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Using resources more efficiently also has a role to play in promoting food security</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as part of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> wider work to make sure the UK has a secure, environmentally sustainable, affordable supply of food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Research for Defra has shown </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that using resources such as energy, water and raw materials more efficiently can generate savings for UK businesses of up to £23 billion a year: while this is spread across the economy as a whole, the food chain makes a significant contribution to it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r recent years the Government has funded WRAP to work with the food industry to help it realise these savings and reduce food waste.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Globally, agriculture uses 70% of fresh water and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">creates 30% of global GHG emissions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(across the supply chain) and is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">main driver of deforestation and land use change which impacts on climate change and biodiversity.  At the same time competition for global resources will increase from other sectors.  We are therefore working to drive more sustainable agriculture includin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g improvements in productivity through sustainable intensification, reductions in post-harvest losses and climate-smart technology to support both global and UK food security.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Detail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Trade policy – overall UK approach</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Overseas trade and inward investment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are vital for the UK’s prosperity. The Government aims to help UK businesses succeed internationally and encourage overseas companies to work with the UK. The UK Government is working actively through the EU and internationally to reduce barriers to trade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and improve market access multilaterally through the World Trade Organisation as well as through bilateral free trade agreements.  It is also working with industry to open up priority export markets with third countries, and supports companies to understa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd and make the most of export opportunities. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">EU food security</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The impact of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CAP and EU trade policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> on global food security</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK view is that the CAP, combined with EU trade policy, has a negative impact on global food security, by: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Limiting productivity growth: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">farm subsidies in the CAP do not encourage food security. Without direct payments, farmers would face market prices without the cushion of subsidy. Farm </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">subsidies can allow inefficient farmers to continue to operate a farm rat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">her than exit the industry. This prevents the land being used by more efficient farmers and so the system of direct payments can dampen productivity growth in the EU agriculture sector. This will reduce the EU’s ability to make an effective contribution to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> global food security.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Keeping prices high</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: price support and other market interventions within CAP have historically resulted in prices that are much higher than they would otherwise be. The impact of price support measures has diminis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hed but is still sig</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nificant, at least in part due to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">previous CAP reforms, and this is an important step for improving global food security. In the most recent CAP reforms, the removal of one of the last production controls, sugar beet quotas, represents a step forward.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Limi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ting free trade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: a secure and diversified supply is one important aspect of food security, which can be best achieved with an open global trading system. The EU continues to implement high agricultural import tariffs to most countries, which are significan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tly higher than for non-agricultural products. Trade barriers make our access to global supplies more difficult and also reduce incentives to increase production outside the EU.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EU applied agricultural tariffs are much higher than on industrial goods:</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 54pt"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="482" height="120" alt="" /></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">     </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pplied </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ariffs on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">elected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ommodities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2012</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></p><div style="text-align:center"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin:0 auto"><tr style="height:15pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:134pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:48pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">beef</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:48pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">lamb</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:48pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">butter</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:48pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cheese</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:48pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">sugar</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:48pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">chicken</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:15pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:134pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Total Ad-Valorem Equivalent (AVE) Tariff</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:48pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">88%</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:48pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">62%</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:48pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">71%</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:48pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">42%</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:48pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">70%</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:48pt"><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">26%</span></p></td></tr></table></div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AVE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is a tariff presented as a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">percentage of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">value of goods</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cleared through customs. Given that the price</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and hence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> value of agricultural commodities on international markets is volatile, AVE tariff figures related to agriculture can be quite variable between years. Nevertheless, it is clear that the EU still applies markedly high tariffs on imported livestock, dairy a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd sugar products which act to significantly increase the price of those commodities in Europe. Accordingly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> these tariffs not only raise the price of food to consumers but also harm the competitiveness of the European food manufacturing industry who have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to pay more for their inputs. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Biofuels</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the context of rising demand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and against the backdrop of future climate change, biofuel policies have been cited as potentially increasing risks to food security.  The Government believes that the primary goal of agriculture must be food production and that the production of biomass f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or bioenergy must not undermine food security in the UK or internationally. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">17.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To the extent that biofuels and biomass policies result in an increase in aggregate demand for agricultural feedstocks and/or agricultural land, they will result in higher agricu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ltural product prices over the medium term than would have otherwise been the case.</span><span style="color:#c00000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Recent analysis by Defra’s modelling team suggests biofuels support at the EU level could have a medium-term price impact on feedstocks used for biofuels production. Averag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e EU wheat and oilseed prices are projected to be 5% and 17% higher than without EU biofuel policy with knock on impacts downstream in the vegetable oil market. This is broadly consistent with modelling by others.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">18.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here is a distinct question about the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">extent to which biofuel policies have contributed to recent international agricultural price spikes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> thorough cross-Whitehall analysis of the agricultural price spikes of 2007/8 concluded that biofuels had a relatively small contribution in 2008, particu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">larly as far as wheat was concerned. However, that report also raised a question about the impact of biofuel support policies on the volatility of international prices. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">19.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n the Government’s 2012 Bioenergy strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we explored mechanisms for mitigating ag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ricultural price spikes through introducing flexibility into biofuels mandates or other measures</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This work reveal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the significant potential associated with a mechanism that allows market forces to direct grain between biofuels, animal feed and food markets during a temporary supply shortage and price spike. The report did not examine specifically the implications of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this idea for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> bioenergy markets and stopped short of examining a particular mechanism. We are considering further work to appraise the merits of more specific proposals. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">20.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government continues to negotiate within Europe to ensure that food production r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">emains at the core of the EU’s consideration of biofuel policy and to promote the development of ‘advanced biofuels’ derived from wastes and residues, which could significantly reduce the direct competition for food feedstocks.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In addition the UK has suppo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the UN and the World Bank</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to develop the Responsible Agricultural Investment principles (RAI) and the Voluntary Guidelines on land use which will help to set voluntary international standards for investment in agricultural production inclu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ding biofuels. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Productivity</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">21.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CAP, trade barriers and biofuels policy all matter because of their direct impacts on food prices.  They also matter because of their impact (along with, for example, R&amp;D) on agricultural productivity.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ecent Defra </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">modelling demonstrates the potential benefits</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of agricultural productivity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Assuming that efficiency and productivity improvements in the EU express themselves as yield improvements, and that annual yield improvements were to be double </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">their current (rela</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tively low) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">level,</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the impact on EU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agricultural prices relative to a 2020 baseline would be significant: 18% lower for wheat, 31% lower for coarse grains (maize and barley), 16% lower for beef and veal, 9% lower for both poultry and pork, 21% lower for m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ilk and butter, and 19% lower for cheese. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">all of the commodities referred to, both the EU production figures and net trade position would also be higher/better than the 2020 baseline projections. The estimated impact on 2020 prices (as well as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">production and the trade balance) is even more significant for grains and meat, if instead one assumes that the EU12 close the current productivity gap with the EU15 by 2020.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">22.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst it may be difficult to model precisely the productivity impact of any giv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">en policy reform, it is clear that modest improvements in productivity result in tangible improvements in consumer prices. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gricultural productivity matters for a whole range of reasons, including food security.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Common Fisheries Policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (CFP)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">23.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Fishing at su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stainable levels, and removing the waste of discarding, will allow us to maximise the yield we can take from our seas in the long term, providing a more stable supply of fish to EU consumers.  Growing populations, growing demand for protein, and growing aw</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">areness of the problems facing the marine environment should provide real opportunities to market and profit from stocks that are managed well.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">24.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EU Member States reached agreement to a historic deal to reform the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CFP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in June this year.  Despite a difficult </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and protracted negotiation, the UK stood firm on its key priorities, securing a robust ban on the discarding of fish with binding timelines, a process for regionalised decision-making, and legally binding commitments to fish sustainably. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">25.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These reforms are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> expected to become law from January 2014, and will benefit fishermen, the food supply chain, and the marine environment.  The reforms agreed provide a crucial opportunity to overcome the failings of the past and put the CFP on a sustainable footing, safeg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uarding the supply of fish to UK and EU markets for future generations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">26.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Improvements to the CFP’s external dimension will also ensure we apply the same principles of sustainability outside EU waters as within.  Europe is the world’s biggest fisheries mark</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">et and can play a vital role in the global governance of fish stocks and delivering a sustainable future. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Resource efficiency in the food and drink supply chain</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">27.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As part of its wider work to make sure the UK has a secure, environmentally sustainable, affor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dable supply of food, the UK government is encouraging the UK food and drink industry to use resources more sustainably. Lead trade associations and major businesses have developed sustainability strategies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> e.g. the British Retail Consortium’s ‘A Better R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">etailing Climate’, and the Food and Drink Federation’s ‘Five-fold Environmental Ambition’.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">28.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, the situation is patchy and further action is needed to improve resource efficiency. Rather than turning immediately to regulation to drive change, the Gove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rnment aims to encourage collaborative voluntary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> action</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The Product Sustainability Forum (PSF) action on groceries, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Soft Drinks Roadmap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the UK Statement on Sustainable Palm Oil are recent examples.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Food waste</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">29.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The UK is committed to playing its part in global efforts to reduce food waste, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">including post-harvest losses,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which in turn will reduce the environmental impacts of the food supply chain, and save valuable resources such as water, land and energy used to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> produce food which ultimately is not eaten. In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">addition, it will deliver a more efficient supply chain where supply and production of food will be closer to the requirement of consumers. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">30.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> seen as a leader in the EU on food waste prevention. We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have worked very successfully with industry to reduce supply chain food and packaging waste by</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7.4%</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">over the last 3 years, while household food waste is down by even more - 15% since 2007. This has been achieved through initiatives such as the Courtauld Co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mmitment voluntary agreement with the retail and manufacturing sector (the latest phase of which</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has prevented a total of 1.7 million tonnes of food and packaging waste, saving</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">around £3.1bn), the Hospitality and Food Service Agreement, and by supporting W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RAP’s Love Food Hate Waste campaign, which helps consumers make informed choices on reducing food waste and save money.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">EU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ustainable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">onsumption and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">roduction activity</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">31.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The EU Commission’s 2011 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Roadmap to a Resource Efficient Europe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> outlines a competitiveness and growth plan for 2050 that is based on a sustainable use of natural resources. The Roadmap identifies the food and drink sector as key priority area in view of its environmental impacts and has a milestone to reduce the food </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chain’s resource inputs by 20% by 2020. It also states that the Commission will assess how best to limit waste throughout the food supply chain, and consider ways to lower the environmental impact of food production and consumption patterns via a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Communica</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">tion on Sustainable Food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which went out for consultation in October 2013 and is due to be published in Spring 2014. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">32.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> been working closely with the Commission and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> other Member S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tates </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">regarding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the communication on sustainable food. Defra met</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> members of the food and drink sector before responding to the Commission’s consultation in October. Defra also convened a meeting between interested parties and the Commission to ensure that the Commission is aware of the many sustainability and resource-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">efficiency initiatives undertaken by the UK food industry in recent years. During 2013, Government also brought together a wide range of stakeholders to discuss the role of diet and consumption in the sustainability of the food system, and the roles of dif</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ferent sectors (consumers, media, private sector, government) in addressing consumption patterns.  </span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The relationship between the price of food and the cost of producing it</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Key points:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is not the role of Government to set retail food prices.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The main co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntribution that Government can make is through pursuing measures that promote open competition and free markets such as those outlined </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">above </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in response to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the first Committee question. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is also a role for Government in ensuring that markets operate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">transparently to ensure that price signals are properly transmitted through the supply chain, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e.g.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through measures such as the Grocer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Code Adjudicator in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A challenge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> identified by the 2011 Foresight report is that of maintaining biodiversity a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd ecosystem services which are critical for supporting food production in the long term, but the value of which are not fully reflected in the costs of food production. This was a key focus of the 2011 Natural Environment White Paper and work is going on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to address this at international level and in the UK, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e.g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through the Economics of Biodiversity study</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the International Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the work of the Natural Capital Committee in the UK.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Detail:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">33.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK food chain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is competitive relative to many other European countries. According to Eurostat, food prices in Germany are 2% more expensive than the UK. In France</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> they are 5% more expensive, and in Ireland 13% - UK consumers are benefiting from our competitive market. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">34.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, in a competitive market there is less slack when underlying prices do rise. So when there are changes in the fundamental drivers of food price inflation (commodity prices, exchange rate, oil prices), consumer prices will adjust to those underlyin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g changes. Whilst </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">food prices have risen faster than our neighbours, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">average</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">price of food remains lower.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">35.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Past Competition Commission Inquiries found that, in many important respects, competition in the UK groceries industry is effective and deliv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ers good outcomes for consumers. However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Competition Commission did identify</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> some issues to do with retailers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> relationships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">with the rest of the supply chain and retailer concentration in certain local markets. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Groceries Code Adjudicator</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> (GCA)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">36.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he aim of the GCA is to promote a stronger and more efficient groceries market</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> bringing better value to consumers through increasing trust between suppliers and retailers by changing their behaviour to follow the Groceries Supply Code of Practice. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">37.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">GCA will help to ensure a fairer relationship between big retailers and their suppliers by supporting innovation and investment and preventing supermarkets passing on excessive risk and cost to suppliers.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">This will provide greater stability throughout the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">supply chain and help consumers, who will benefit from a more robust groceries market.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">It will not prevent r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">etailers from securing the best deals and passing on benefits to consumers. Prices are a commercial matter, agreed by private negotiation within the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> parameters of competition law.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Valuing b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">iodiversity and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">cosystem </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ervices</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">38.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> There is a huge effort nationally and internationally to understand and use ecosystem services values, through the follow up to the National Ecosystem Assessment, the Economics of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Ecosystems and Biodiversity study</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the Intergovernmental Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services. In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England, the importance of improving the measurement and valuation of ecosystem services will underpin the work of the Natural Capital Committ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ee who will be advising </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment on the state of English natural capital.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">39.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Natural Environment White Paper recognised that a healthy natural environment is the foundation of sustained economic growth, prospering communities and personal wellbeing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It sets out how the value of nature can be mainstreamed across our society by facilitating local action; strengthening the connections between people and nature; creating a green economy and showing leadership in the EU and internationally.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Natural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Capital Committee was established to help us better understand the state of the natural environment and how this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ffects the economy and wider wellbeing, with its first report released in April 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The business-led Ecosystems Market Taskforce was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">established, and reported its findings on potential new markets that create opportunities for growth and also benefit the environment. The Government response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is now being taken forward.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Payment for Ecosystem Services is stimulating innovative new approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es to encourage investment in the natural environment.  A programme of demonstration pilot projects has been funded, plus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> best practice guide to help others set up further PES schemes, along with a Defra Action Plan.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The implications of volatility in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">e global food supply and demand for UK food security</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Key points:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Volatility is an inherent characteristic of agricultural commodity markets – it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cannot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be designed out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Agricultural commodity prices are one of the key drivers of UK retail food price</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> inflation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, alongside global </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> prices and exchange rates, both of which are subject to similar volatility.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK food sector is a highly competitive one.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is reflected in the fact that retail food price</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the UK are on the whole lower than in many</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> other European countries.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">corollary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of this is that changes in world commodity prices tend to feed through more fully (although usually with a significant time lag) to retail food prices in the UK than in some other countries.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On balance, reliabl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e evi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dence suggests scepticism </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that speculation in agricultural futures markets has played a significant causal role in agricultural price volatility, but the Government continues to monitor relevant research.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Volatility in global food supply has a greater impa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ct on consumers in developing countries than in the UK and EU. Poverty rather than food availability is the main cause of food insecurity and hunger.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As the world becomes increasingly urbanised, the ability to buy rather than grow enough food will become m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ore dominant as the determinant of food and nutrition security in developing countries.  Food security and nutrition are priorities for the Government and are a major focus of Department for International Development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (DfID)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> programmes.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Detail:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Agricultural</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> commodity markets</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">40.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Price volatility is an inherent characteristic of global agricultural commodity markets and has long characterised them. This is due to the dependence of production on weather patterns, the relative insensitivity of demand to food price changes, and produc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion lags.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">41.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some degree of price volatility is therefore normal but volatility tends to be highest in ‘thin’ international markets where a small proportion of global production is traded (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e.g.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the global rice market) or when there are adverse policy resp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">onses to market developments such as export bans. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However historic attempts to manage price levels and/or reduce price volatility have been unsuccessful.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">42.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Despite the agricultural price spikes experienced in 2007/8 and more recently, there is little evidenc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e to suggest that price volatility has increased over time. Indeed, analysis for the Foresight report concluded that agricultural price volatility over the two most recent decades has generally been lower than in the 1970s and 1980s. Furthermore, it should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be noted that spikes seen in the early 1970s were far larger in real terms (i.e. accounting for inflation) than recent spikes. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">43.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However there is a risk that price volatility (and the frequency of price spikes) could increase in the future, mainly due to m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ore volatile energy prices and extreme weather events associated with climate change. Conversely, increased trade between countries, deeper international markets for agricultural goods and the avoidance of adverse policy responses should act to reduce futu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re price volatility.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">44.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is important to bear in mind that the volatility (and level) of commodity prices is of more importance to consumers in developing countries than in developed countries. This is firstly because poorer individuals spend a much greate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r proportion of their income on food, and secondly because in developed countries the price of food to consumers is often only weakly connected to the cost of basic commodities, with other inputs like energy, labour and packaging being more important. For </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">example, the price of wheat accounts for only 11% of the cost of a loaf of bread in the UK. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">45.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although commodity prices are only weakly related to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of some prices, modelling</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> demonstrates that alongside exchange rates and oil prices, they are the l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">argest drivers of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inflation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in retail food prices. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">46.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst global commodity markets have significant impacts on retail food price inflation, there is a lag between commodity price rises and their impact on retail food price inflation if for example, there </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">may be contracts in place which prevent the full price increase being immediately passed on. Given that: contracts may be of differing lengths; price changes of different commodities are not perfectly correlated; and that there are other, non-commodity pri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce factors driving food price inflation, then any volatility on commodities markets will be significantly moderated before their transmission to consumer prices.   </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Speculation</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">47.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government recognises that there is a range of views in respect of the role</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that may have been played by commodity speculation in recent food p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rice spikes. On balance, reliable evidence suggests</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> scepticism that speculation in agricultural futures markets has played a significant causal role in agricultural price volatility. However, the Government continues to monitor relevant research with interest. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">48.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is also important to note that trading in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">commodity markets plays an important role in providing liquidity in these markets and that liquidity is essential to the effective functioning of these markets. Against the backdrop of climate change, and the possibility that international agricultural pri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ces may become more volatile over time, the role of agricultural futures and options markets and the liquidity they rely on, become more important.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Volatility and developing countries</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">49.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK Government recognises the damaging impact of high food prices and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> food price volatility on poor consumers in developing countries.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">High price volatility reduces the benefits of higher prices for net producers. For food producing households, price volatility makes the returns to increased production more uncertain and so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> acts as a disincentive to further investment.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfID and Defra are planning research to better understand the extent to which commodity price changes impact on consumers, producers and poverty in the developing world.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">50.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK Government believes that free tr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ade and effective and efficient markets provide a greater level of food security than large-scale, public food stocks designed to manage price volatility at national or international level. Experience to date suggests such stocks are expensive to run, with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> implications for fiscal positions, and are likely to crowd out private sector stocking initiatives and would therefore not necessarily stabilise prices. D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ID supports, in principle, proposals for regional emergency humanitarian food stocks in high risk re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gions such as the Sahel, to improve the speed and effectiveness of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">response to humanitarian disasters. Carefully targeted social safety nets are also important to help poor consumers in developing countries cope with price inflation.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">51.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is working internationally, particularly with other members of the G20, to liberalise trade and make commodity markets function more efficiently. The Government is promoting greater sharing of information on existing stocks, and discouraging disruptive act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ions such as export bans, which limit supplies and drive up prices.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">AMIS</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">52.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Agriculture Market Information System (AMIS) is a G20 initiative which seeks to improve agricultural market transparency, information sharing and facilitate policy coordination be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tween major producing, exporting and importing countries. A central task is its work to develop indicators to monitor market and policy drivers that impact on global food prices and global food price volatility. The AMIS Rapid Response Forum promotes early</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> discussion between countries concerning abnormal market conditions and allows for the development of shared strategies. AMIS will not necessarily prevent price increases or some level of volatility but can help improve understanding of markets and enhance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> policy coordination in times of crisis. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">53.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AMIS has made valuable progress since it was initially set up two years ago.  The UK is an active participant in all aspects of AMIS’ work and encourages the contribution of timely and high quality data around key </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">indicators, such as stock levels, from all members through the Global Food Information Group.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Post-2015 Development Framework</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">54.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is pushing for an ambitious and compelling set of new global development goals to take effect when the Millenni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">um Development G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> conclude in 2015.  These are an opportunity to bring people and planet together to eradicate poverty and achieve shared prosperity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> including through improved food security and nutrition, sustainable natural resource</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (includ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing water and energy), and good governance and effective institutions.  </span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The potential value and contribution of science and GM technology to UK food security</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Key points</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Investment in science and technology is essential in the light of the scale of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">global food security challenge identified in the 2011 Foresight report.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In response to the Foresight report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Government brought together </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">public funders, industry and the third sector through the Government Chief Scientist’s Food Research Partnership an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Global Food Security </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(GFS) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to set the agenda and maximise the impact of research and innovation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The Government is currently investing over £4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">0m a year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on agri-food research which is coordinated by the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">GFS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through themes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">set out in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Cross-Government Food Research and Innovation Strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the recently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">published </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Global Food Security Strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">refresh</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As well as representing a major research challenge, this set of issues also represents a significant economic opportunity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for the UK.  Agricultural science and technology is one of the world’s fastest growing markets. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We need a whole range of agricultural technologies and innovations to ensure that we have the food to feed a growing world population: as part of that, we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">need to ensure that the potential of any new or emerging technology is researched and applied where it makes sense to do so. This applies to GM technology but equally to a range of other technologies, such as nanotechnology. Issues of consumer trust and ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ceptability are a key part of agricultural technology development.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Detail:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">55.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government’s Agri-Tech Strategy</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> published jointly by BIS, Defra and DfID in July 2013, aims to re-position the UK as a world leader in the global challenge of the sustainable i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntensification of agriculture, producing more with less input and impact. Government is investing £160m in translational research led and co-funded by industry to strengthen links between science and technology to drive innovation and its uptake into farmi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng to improve the efficiency, cost effectiveness, and productivity in agriculture; increase access and uptake of knowledge transfer; and promote better access to international markets and export opportunities. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">56.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are also working with the Technology Strat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">egy Board </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(TSB) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to drive innovation to support a more competitive, resilient and sustainable agri-food sector via the £90m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Sustainable A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">griculture and Food Innovation Platform; £4.5M investment in a new Sustainable Intensification Platform to help translat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e knowledge into practice to help farmers; and the £70m Agri-tech Strategy’s catalyst innovation competitions with industry led by TSB (with a £10m contribution from DfID for pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">jects in developing countries.)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">57.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">More widely, Government is building links to s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">trengthen multi-disciplinary research to address food security through EU initiatives such as the Joint Programming Initiative on Agriculture, Food Security and Climate Change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the European Research Area Networks in developing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">common research agenda </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">across Europe; and working closely with the European Commission and other Member States in developing research work programmes under the EU’s Horizon 2020 research and innovation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">programme. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK is also colla</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">borating internationally with Df</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ID and the Chi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nese Ministry of Agriculture on food security via the Sustainable Agriculture Innovation Network (SAIN) and in the Global Research Alliance to find ways to reduce agricultural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">GHG</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> emissions.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">GM and emerging technologies</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Genomics</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">58.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Genomics utilises the recen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t acceleration in gene sequencing technology that has been researched and pioneered in the UK. It allows marker genes to be identified that correspond to the desirable traits observed in naturally occurring varieties of crops. By applying genomics (in a wa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y that was not possible a decade ago) crop varieties can be selectively developed by means of an acceleration of the natural selection process.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Genetic Modification</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">59.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">From the scientific and other evidence it is clear that the responsible use of GM crops cou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ld play an important role alongside other options to help ensure food security.  This conclusion has been supported by a number of important reviews in recent years which have highlighted how science and technology, including GM, will be crucial to making </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agriculture more efficient and sustainable.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">60.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">GM technology is already contributing to UK food security via the extensive use of imported GM livestock feed, soya in particular. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ivestock sector could not operate at the same level without the use of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">imported supplies at prevailing prices.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The majority of global soya production is now GM and this is cheaper than conventional soya.         </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">61.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A major barrier to the development and use of GM crops in Europe is the operation of the relevant EU controls. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> process for authorising GM cultivation is dysfunctional because there is no political consensus on this issue, and only one GM crop has secured EU approval since 1998. The uncertainty around the approval process has deterred GM-related investment and inno</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vation, denying EU farmers and consumers the benefits that would be expected to flow from this.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A recent European Court of Justice ruling has prompted the European Commission to call for a vote by EU Ministers on a GM insect-resistant maize variety. This w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ill be the first such vote since 2007 and may end the current moratorium on authorisations for GM cultivation.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">62.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> negative EU situation is damaging for the future of agriculture both in Europe and in developing countries which may be influenced by it. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> disparity between the EU and other parts of the world on GM uptake continues to grow, this in itself poses a potential threat to our food security. It creates the possibility for traces of non-EU approved GM material to be found in imported commoditi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es like soya.  This undermines the ability to maintain orderly and cost-effective supply chains on which the UK relies.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">63.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Outside Europe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> GM production is already significant whilst in the EU only one GM crop is being grown on a limited scale (an insect-re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sistant maize of no UK interest).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The main existing GM crops offer easier weed and pest control but a range of other GM traits have been commercialised or are in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the development pipeline.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This includes drought-tolerance, disease-resistance, nitrogen-use ef</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ficiency, and improved nutritional characteristics.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">64.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a specific example of how GM cultivation could help the UK, blight-resistant potatoes have been developed which could significantly improve production of this important crop.  It could mean a marked </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">duction in the use of fungicides and an increase in production as losses to the disease are curtailed.  The company BASF had applied for EU approval of a GM blight-resistant potato but later withdrew the application because of the difficult EU situation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he full potential contribution of GM production to the UK will clearly depend on the range of new crop traits that might be developed and adopted over time.    </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">65.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government will continue to argue for the EU to operate a more sensible GM regime. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">upport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> pragmatic and proportionate controls which enable fair market access for GM products that pass a robust safety evaluation. Domestically we are open to, and want to encourage, GM crop research. In recent years there have been several publicly-funded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> research projects in England which have involved GM field trials (work on GM nematode-resistant potatoes by Leeds University, on GM blight-resistant potatoes by the Sainsbury Laboratory, and on GM aphid-repellent wheat by Rothamsted Research). The UK has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a world-class plant science base and should therefore be in a strong position to contribute to advances that will improve food security both at home and in developing countries, including through realising the potential of GM plant breeding.</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">How food a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">nd farming supply chains and the current systems for traceability can contribute to increased resilience</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Key point</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">s:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The size and diversity of the food and farming sectors give substantial resilienc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e to the UK food supply chain.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The ability to provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">alternatives and draw on a variety of sources reduces the risk of serious disruption of food supply.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government nonetheless takes risks to food supply seriously</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">works with the food sector to promote business continuity planning to prepare for a ran</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ge of risks ranging from natural disasters and disruption elsewhere impacting on food supply chains</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to threats to food safety and animal and plant health.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Recent events have highlighted risks to food supply chains from food fraud.  Although food fraud is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not a new issue, the substitution of horsemeat in beef products has shaken consumer confidence.  The Government launched an independent review of the integrity and assurance of food supply networks led by Professor Chris Elliott in June 2013.  An interim r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eport from the review is expected in December, with a final report in spring 2014.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Food businesses have a legal responsibility to ensure the traceability o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f products they are supplying. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Beyond that, full traceability is fundamental to UK food producers mak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing the most of economic opportunities based on high environmental</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and animal welfare standards. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government is active in supporting UK food producers to take advantage of these opportunities through UKTI and Ministerial support for food and drink expor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ters</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and through negotiations to lift market access restrictions in some export markets.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government supports improved country of origin labelling for meat.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Detail:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">66.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The food industry is large, competitive and diverse, and it is the responsibility of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">individual businesses to review business continuity arrangements and plan for dealing with incidents such as extreme weather, flooding, power failures, strikes or excessive staff absences </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e.g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a result of pandemic flu.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">67.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Information from the Defra Food S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tocks Survey (September 2011) indicates that most of the large </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">etailers and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">anufacturers regularly test their ability to cope with emergencies by testing their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">usiness </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ontingency arrangements. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ood </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ndustry has coped well with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a number of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> real-life</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> incidents over the last few years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> had many opportunities to practice, learn and improve their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Business</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ontinuity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lanning arrangements.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Risks to disruption of the food chain</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#464646; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">68.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review recognised the risk from natural disasters as one of the top tier risks facing the UK, and made the continued provision of essential services in such circumstances as one of the Gover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nment’s highest resilience priorities. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">69.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this review,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the Critical Infrastructure Resilience Programme within Cabinet Office developed a systematic, co-ordinated, cross-sector campaign to reduce the disrup</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion caused by natural hazards/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">disaste</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rs to the UK’s critical infrastructure and the essential services they deliver. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">70.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A key output from this programme is the development of Sector Resilience Plans, produced annually by Lead Government Departments working with their infrastructure owners and r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">egulators.  The Plans are part of an ongoing assessment to increase Government’s understanding of the level of resilience of the UK’s critical infrastructure to natural hazards.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">71.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra works with the food industry to promote an understanding in the releva</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt government departments of its dependencies. Defra set up and chairs the Food Chain Emergency Liaison Group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a forum at which other government departments, industry, and the relevant trade associations can share information and jointly consider resilienc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e issues. This Group meets 3 to 4 times a year and on a regular basis as required.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">72.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK Food Security Assessment highlighted that further planning was required to ensure the UK was able to maintain supplies in the event of disruption to ports, as the maj</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ority of the UK’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> food imports arrive that way. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra identified the food products vulnerable to port disruption</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; and it is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">working with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Department for Transport (DfT) to identify the major ports used for the import of these food types and identify sub</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stitute facilities in the event of disruption. The information gathered from these exercises will allow Defra and DfT to work with industry to agree a national plan to manage key food supplies. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">73.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra has also commissioned research that seeks to address bu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ilding the resilience of the food supply chain in the event of a potential major east coast flooding event, and in response to other extreme and volatile weather events.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government Chief Scientist’s Food Re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">earch Partnership has also reviewed the evid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nce underpinning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">resilience of the food supply including risks from cyber terrorism, extreme weather and regulatory obstacles. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Risks to food safety </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#464646; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">74.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Food safety law specifies requirements including the absence of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pathogenic micro-organisms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and safety for consumption</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Food Safety Act 1990 provides the framework for all food legislation in the UK.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">75.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government has a responsibility to ensure that food law is upheld and consumers are protected, but the primary obligation to ensure that f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ood supplied is safe to eat is placed on food businesses. Food businesses must tell the FSA where they have reason to believe that a foodstuff that they have imported, produced, manufactured or distributed does not meet food safety requirements, and must u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se their own approach to exercise due diligence over the food they sell to ensure they are meeting safety and authenticity requirements.  Businesses agree specific specifications with suppliers and suppliers are subject to inspection by such businesses as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">well as local authorit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Many large food businesses also conduct their own testing of food samples.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">76.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The central competent authority in the UK for monitoring and controlling the application of food law is the Food Standards Agency (FSA).  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he maj</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ority of surveillance and enforcement activity to protect the consumer is undertaken locally by local and port health authorities. Local authority staff routinely inspect premises on a risk basis as well as collecting samples which are tested for food safe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty or compositional and labelling compliance.  In 2010-11 89% of food businesses checked were broadly compliant with food safety law.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">77.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Regulation (EC) 178/2002 lays down the EU principles and requirements of food law.  It applies to all stages of production</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, processing and distribution of food and feed.  Around one fifth of all spending to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">check for compliance with food law is at the stage of slaughterhouses, cutting plan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s and primary producers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This reflects EU prescription, the relatively high safety risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of food handling at these stages, and the need to track raw meat to the farms and suppliers for both animal and human health purposes.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">78.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The FSA recognises however the need to rebalance assurance activity so that it more accurately reflects the risk associa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ted with today’s food prod</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ucts and longer supply chains. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The FSA has been taking a lead in influencing at an EU level for changes to official controls so that they are more risk based and proportionate.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Risks to plant health</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">79.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Plant health is now one of Defr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a’s top 4 priorities with increased resources for operational activity and research. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">developed a prioritised risk register, working with the relevant industry sectors and work has also started on plant health contingency planning. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">80.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The current bo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dy of EU legislation covering the agri-food chain including plant health consists of almost 70 pieces of legislation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the European Commission has adopted a proposed package of measures aiming to cut this down to 5. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> committed to pursuing a new</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> regime with faster decision making in response to plant health risks, better risk targeting of such threats and improved enforcement of the rules. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">81.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">created the UK Plant Health Risk Register, potential instability in global food supply from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> shock events is also recognised in the UK Food Security Assessment as a dependency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">82.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the area of food security with developing countries, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> working with UK-CDS in the design of the Natural Hazards Risk Register to deliver early warning for overse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as support. In its final form it should also provide early warning of potential crop pest events that may affect UK food supply and security.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Risks to animal health</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">83.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One of Defra’s priorities is to minimise risks and increase preparedness for animal diseas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e outbreaks, driving growth and competitiveness through improving standards of animal health and welfare.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Animal disease outbreaks and contingency plans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">84.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Published contingency plans set out how an outbreak of exotic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> notifiable disease of animals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dealt with. The impact of disease control p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">olicies on food supply markets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is considered as an integral part of the response through liaison with the food supply chain.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#464646; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Food fraud and labelling </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#464646; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">85.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The horsemeat incident at the start of 2013 highlighted the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">potential impact of a food fraud on the resilience of the food supply chain.  The incident saw the mass recall of a number of products across the EU and had a serious impact on consumer confidence in the food that they were buying or being served.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">86.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">An ind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ependent review of Britain’s food system was launched in June 2013 and will report by Spring 2014.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The review will focus on consumer confidence in the authenticity of food and will identify any weaknesses in food supply networks which could have implicatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ns for food safety and public health.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It will look at the causes that enabled horsemeat fraud, the roles and responsibilities of businesses to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consumers and how to support consumer confidence.  Findings will be used to form recommendations to Government on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> how the UK can increase the resilience of its food systems to fraud.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">87.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government is clear that food fraud is completely unacceptable. Consumers must have confidence in the food they buy and have every right to expect that food is correctly described. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ransparency is key to confidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">88.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government will do whatever is necessary to ensure that British farmers and food manufacturers have access to export markets.  This includes making sure British food is recognised for its rigorous standards and traceab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ility, and that our producers do not get a bad reputation due to the Europe-wide horsemeat incidents.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are working hard to help the British food and farming sectors make the most of their excellent products and high standards.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">89.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Food businesses have howeve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r a legal responsibility to assure traceability.  This means that a food business supplying food products from other food businesses is responsible to its customers for ensuring that everything it sells is safe and is as described.  Such businesses therefo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re must by EU food law assure themselves of the nature, quality and description of what they are supplying.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">90.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On labelling, the food industry is ultimately responsible for making sure that labelling on food is accurate and consumers are not misled. The UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has supported more and better country of origin information that is targeted at meeting the needs of consumer. </span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Whether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food security strategies and planning</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Key points:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At a global level climate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">change is expected to have two distinct impacts on food production in the long term:  gradual impacts resulting from projected changes in global temperatures and rainfall levels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and more transient impacts resulting from an expected increase in the freque</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cy of extreme weather events. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Current projections suggest that climate change will generally tend to reduce yields at the global level, but there are still key evidence gaps.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To the extent that there is greater disruption from extreme weather events, thi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s highlights the importance of international trade in managing volatility and mitigating global price rises.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At the UK level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the 2012 Climate Change Risk A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ssessment identifies the risks and opportunities related to climate change. The next such assessment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will be published in January 2017 and is currently being scoped</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is the responsibility of individual food businesses to review business continuity plans for dealing with incidents such as extreme weather.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many of the larger food manufacturers and retai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lers regularly test their contingency plans.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Detail:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Climate change and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> projected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> impacts on volatility </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">91.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra recently commissioned a review of the literature on global food security modelling with a focus on climatic factors. Of models that explicitly co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nsider scenarios around climate change, it is projected that climate change will generally tend to reduce yields at the global level – although there are stark differences in impacts across regions – and raise crop prices. However, there are still key evid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ence gaps around the impacts of CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> levels and precipitation patterns on crop yields which mean such results should be treated with caution. The IPCC suggest that extreme weather events could have a more significant impact on food security than gradual cli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mate changes, though such extreme weather events are typically left out of formal modelling exercises because their location, severity and nature are not known. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">92.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is acknowledged that in light of climate change, international trade will become more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">important in managing volatility and mitigating global price rises from harvest disruption and extreme weather events.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UK Climate Change Risk Assessment </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">93.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In January last year Defra published the first UK Climate Change Risk Assessment (CCRA), as required by the Climate Change Act 2008, which brought together the best available evidence using a consistent framework to identify the risks and opportunities rel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ated to climate change. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">94.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CCRA assessed climate risks for the UK using the UK Climate Projections (UKCP09) for three time periods – 30-year periods centred on the 2020s, 2050s and 2080s and three emission scenarios. The CCRA classified risks and opportu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nities into three broad impact classes, ‘low’, ‘medium’ and ‘high’ and also identified those risks that are highly uncertain and difficult to quantify. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The method focused attention on risks where decisions need to be made in the near future (i.e. in the ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">xt 5 years).</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">95.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CCRA identifies a number of impacts on domestic agriculture. These impacts include increasing water demand coupled with decreasing availability, drier soils, reduced soil quality and soil erosion, increased flood risk to high quality agric</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ultural land and the impacts of heat on livestock productivity and welfare. The changing climate may allow new pests, diseases and other invasive species to enter the country, or allow existing examples to spread further or become more of a risk. An increa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se in extreme weather events such as droughts, floods and severe storms could result in unexpected reductions in productivity.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">96.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is also the potential for positive impacts of climate change, including increases in yield and productivity of existing cro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ps and grassland as well as the opportunity to introduce new crops. However these opportunities will only come </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to pass if other factors which a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ffect growth, such as water availability, are not limiting.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">97.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The second CCRA is currently being scoped and will be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> published by January 2017. Defra is working closely with other Government Departments and interested parties to ensure that we identify the most important areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for the assessment to focus on.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The role of science</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">98.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lobal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">esearch </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lliance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n Agricultur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al Greenhouse Gases, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">launched </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Dec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ember 2009</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at the UN Climate Change Conference in Copenhagen is an international collaboration between over 30 countries including the UK which brings together research, extension of technologies and practices that will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">help deliver ways to grow more food, more climate resistant food systems without increasing GHG emissions.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">99.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Met Office Hadley Centre is coordinating yearly initialised decadal predictions to build better medium-term forecasting. This work uses multiple </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">climate models and is carried out in collaboration with international partners. It will provide government and the wider society, including farmers, with better information to drive the process of climate adaptation.</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The obstacles facing food producers, i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">ncluding small farmers, seeking to increase production and access new markets</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Key points:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra has commissioned research to investigate the obstacles to food producers exporting and one study specifically on small and medium sized enterprises.  These highlighted a lack of knowledge of potential export markets and of the potential benefits of e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">xporting, availability of resources, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">particularly management time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and technical barriers and associated bureaucracy.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra is working with the food industry and UKT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to help food and drink exporters overcome these obstacles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and in particular to help sma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ller businesses access export markets for the first time.  Specific commitments are set out in the Food and Drink Exports Action Plan, which was re-launched in November 2013.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra is also working with industry to remove any barriers preventing UK producer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s from making the most of opportunities to supply the UK market.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Detail:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Food exports</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">100.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sustained growth in the food and drink in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dustry is a priority for Defra. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK has a long, proud and strong heritage of producing high quality, safe and excellent tastin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g food. The sector is important to the UK, contributing £96 billion annually</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a wide range of food and drink that is known throughout the world.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n 2012 UK exports amounted to £18.2bn - nearly 50% higher than a decade ago. Scotch Whisky exports ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e nearly £4.3bn and we export over £2bn of meat.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">101.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The increasing global population, rising middle class and incomes are leading to demand for western products and so represents opportunities for UK producers. There is huge potential to export more to establ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ished and also high growth markets in Brazil, Russia, India and China, where these currently represent only 3% of our total export market.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Barriers to exporting</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">102.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are existing studies that highlight barriers, or obstacles, to export, including: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lack</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">knowledge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f potential export markets and opportunities in overseas markets</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a lack of awareness of the financial and non</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">financial benefits arising from exporting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and so failing to commit sufficient resources to exporting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">availability of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">resource</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – i.e.,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> management time or staff for planning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and deve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">loping international activity. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This also includes financial constraints</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Bureaucracy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> associated with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> meeting other countries’ biosecurity requirements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> such as sanitary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and phytosanitary requir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and legal regulations or standards, along with cultural and linguistic barriers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">isk and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uncertainty in overseas markets.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">103.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A Defra funded 2012 report by University of Plymouth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ‘Obstacles to export growth for small and medium sized Agrifood companies’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> found that obstacles to exporting experienced by agrifood SMEs were broadly similar to those identified in other sectors, with the most significant barriers being finding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">manageme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt time, identifying who to make contact with, dealing with legal or tax regulations or standards overseas and protecting IP. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">104.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Similarly, amongst agrifood businesses that did not export, the most significant perceived barriers were finding the necessary ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nagement time to devote to doing business in an overseas country, followed by the costs associated with doing business overseas.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Food and Drink Exports Action Plan</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">105.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ndustry are therefore working together to promote UK industry and access</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> markets.  The Exports Action Plan first launched in 2012 outlined this joint work. The Plan was refreshed in the autumn of 2013 to reflect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment commitment to increase exports by delivering half a billion pounds of value to the UK economy through ass</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">isting up to 1,000 food and drink companies with their international growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and contributing to wider aims to increase exports by at least £1bn by October 2015. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The full list of commitments can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be found in the </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-food-and-drink-international-action-plan"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Action Plan</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This includes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">brigading </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ndustry and Government to create a single strong UK brand identity to increase the visibility of UK food and drink </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at the world's major food events and exhibitions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and work to lift trade barriers, promote trade and maintain access to markets already opened.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">106.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">businesses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> faced a number of barriers to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> access global markets due to restrictions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">imposed by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> importing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">countries. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For example, exports for ruminant meat are restricted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">due to BSE and TSE concerns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in some countries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are working closely with the in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dustry and the British Embassy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in those countries to remove these barriers</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and have plans in place to mitigat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e the impact on exports</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of an animal disease outbreak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Where export health certificates are required</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> we work with the industry to identify priority markets and negotiate the wording acceptable to the importing country. We are also improving the system of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">processing export health certification applications. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Role of innovation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">remov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> obstacles</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">107.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government recognises the need to remove key obstacles to scientific development in the UK and its uptake into practice by farmers to support access to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> marke</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and is working towards boosting investment in innovation.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">108.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the agriculture sector, we understand that the small average size of farm businesses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> can limit ability to invest in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and adopt innovations owing to the costs associated with acquiring reliable information on new technologies and processes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the practical difficulties of protecting intellectual property, brands and trademarks, whilst</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recognising that being small </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can also bring advantages to implementing change.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">109.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are taking steps to simplify funding and intellectual property arrangements and ensure business participation and practical translation of resear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ch through a number of channels, e.g. through the Agri-Te</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ch Strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">110.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Technology Strategy Board’s (TSB) Sustainable Agriculture and Food Innovation Platform also provides a key route to support innovation through funding of industry-led collaborative research and development with the academic research base.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This is funded jointly with Defra, the Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council (BBSRC) and the Scottish Government, providing government investment of up to £90m over five years.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">111.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Additional targeted instruments include the Crop Improveme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt Research Club, a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">five-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">year, £7m partnership between BBSRC, the Scottish Government and an industry consortium aimed at supporting research leading to sustainable improvements in crop productivity and crop quality. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Ways of increasing self-sufficiency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> in products for which the UK has a comparative advantage</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Key points:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are different ways of measuring self-sufficiency.  The most useful measure, known as the ‘production to supply ratio’ measures domestic production (including exports) as a proporti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on of domestic co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nsumption (including imports). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This stood at 62% for all food in 2012 and 76% for foods indigenous to the UK. Although lower than recent decades, this level is not low when viewed in the context of the last 150 years.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK’s production </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and trade patterns are determined by comparative advantage – our trade in food reflects this. However, there may be sectors where the UK could increase the production to supply ratio.  The key to UK producers exploiting market opportunities at home and abr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oad is competitiveness.  It is up to the food supply chain to innovate and invest in order to improve their productivity.  But the Government is exploring areas where there may be barriers to UK producers from fully exploiting their comparative advantage, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as well as breaking down barriers to UK food and drink exports accessing foreign markets.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While improvements in productivity which lead to the UK increasing its domestic production will benefit the food chain and the UK economy more generally, a higher pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">duction to supply ratio does not necessarily equate to improved food security.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">urrent positive assessments of the UK food chain’s security of supply are based in part on the diversity of our food supplies and the resilience this provides.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK believes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that secure food supplies are derived from being fully integrated into a well-functioning and transparent global market, rather than relying on only UK production. Global markets provide insurance against local or regional weather effects, as well as othe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r events and allow the UK consumers and businesses to benefit from improvements around the globe which reduce prices and improve quality. Increasing domestic production of certain products does not alter this approach to food security – the benefits of bei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng integrated into global markets remain.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Detail:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Self-sufficiency and the production to supply ratio</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">112.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Self-sufficiency is used to convey different meanings by different commentators. It is often used as shorthand for the production to supply ratio.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">113.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">duction to supply ratio also takes into account net trade. Given that we export significant amounts of indigenous food, the proportion of food that is consumed domestically from domestic production is lower than the production to supply ratio. For 2012, th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e UK’s production of indigenous type food, that is, food stuffs that the UK can produce domestically, was 76% of total supply. These figures have fallen in recent decades from their peaks in the 1980’s. However, the production to supply ratio in this perio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d was inflated by the effect of the CAP, which resulted in Europe-wide surpluses and unnecessarily high prices for consumers. Taking a longer view of history, the current production to supply ratio is similar to that of the second half of the 19</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">entury.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Indeed it is higher than that of the first half of the 20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> century, at some points very significantly so, even until into the 1960’s. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">114.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Comparative advantage is an economic concept which states that a country will specialise in, and therefore export, prod</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uction of a good in which it has a relative cost advantage. In practical terms, comparative advantage is revealed by a country’s pattern of trade. For products in which the UK has a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">comparative advantage, the UK will therefore already have production in ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cess of consumption: in other words, the UK will be a net exporter of that product. The production to supply ratio figures illustrate that the UK does not have a revealed comparative advantage across food production in general. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">115.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, there may be secto</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rs where the UK could increase the production to supply ratio, through cost-effectively increasing overall production. It would be up to producers whether any increase would be supplied to the domestic or export market. The Government is exploring areas wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ere there may be barriers to UK producers from fully exploiting their comparative advantage and accessing the domestic market, as well as breaking down barriers to UK food and drink exports accessing foreign markets. The key to UK producers exploiting mark</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">et opportunities at home and abroad is competitiveness – improvements in productivity will allow producers to compete with international producers of equivalent goods, though market access barriers imposed by importing can make it difficult for exporters t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o fully exploit their comparative advantage. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">116.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is up to the food supply chain to innovate and invest in order to improve their productivity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and take advantage of export opportunities, but Government’s role is to ensure that the policy and regulatory environment assists industry as much as possible in doing so. Improvements in productivity which lead to the UK increasing its production will ben</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">efit the food chain and the UK economy more generally. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">117.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra continues to work closely with industry to identify policy and regulatory issues which may impact on the competitiveness of the sector.  The Secretary of State met representatives from across th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e industry and the devolved administrations in July 2013 to discuss how to increase the competitiveness of the sector.  Issues being explored following that discussion include the importance of taking forward EU negotiations on labelling to make it easier </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for consumers to identify where their food comes from, exploring sector-specific issues, examining how we can overcome any barriers to domestic producers competing effectively for public sector contracts, and ways of supporting growth in the food and drink</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sector at local level.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Increasing market share for products in which the UK has a comparative advantage</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">118.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government’s goal is to support and develop British farming, to encourage sustainable food production, and a sector which is more productive and co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mpetitive. Our role within that is to help create the right conditions and remove obstacles so that farming businesses can operate successfully, increase their productivity, and respond to market signals and demand.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">119.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We take a range of steps to help support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the industry in this respect: as stated, we have been seeking to reform the Common Agricultural Policy to reduce the industry’s dependency on direct subsidies over time. We are currently consulting on the implementation of the new CAP, including how we mi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ght use the future Rural Development Programme for this purpose. Support for innovation and technology are key factors in improving the industry’s productivity, as set out in the Agri-Tech Strategy and explored in this paper.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">120.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">During 2011-2012 we worked in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">partnership with the food and farming industry and environmental organisations to examine how we might increase food production whilst improving the environment. This triggered a range of new activities, such as the creation of a ‘Sustainable Intensificati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on Research Platform’ and a ‘Future of Farming Review’. This review was undertaken by a core group of key individuals from across the farming sector who examined issues such as routes of entry into employment in agriculture, barriers to starting these care</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ers and how new entrants can be better supported. The Review reported in July 2013 and the group are working jointly with Government and wider industry to take forward the recommendations. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">121.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Going forward, we need to attract the brightest and best entrepren</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eurs to the farming profession and to the food sector more generally. Government works with the industry-led skills agenda, supporting development of the highly skilled workforce the sector will need for the future. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">122.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since 2011, we have worked with the Nat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ional Skills Academy for Food and Drink to support the Skills Action Plan for the Food Supply Chain, which aimed to tackle skills shortages in the food supply chain.  Earlier in 2013, the National Skills Academy announced that their target for creation of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">50 000 apprenticeships across the food supply chain had been exceeded.  More recently, the food and drink sector has signed up as part of the first group of Apprenticeship Trailblazers developing new apprenticeship standards and assessment approaches.  201</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3 has also seen the launch of the innovative MEng in Food Engineering at Sheffield Hallam University and the associated National Centre of Excellence for Food Engineering, and further innovative work to encourage young people into the sector by the Food an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d Drink Federation and the IGD.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">123.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK’s comparative advantage does not only relate to the nature of our geography and environment, but also to the areas where we have developed a strong skills capability and reputation. Our industry has high standards of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">animal health and welfare and traceability,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and we have highly innovative food manufacturing and retailing sectors. The Government will continue to look for ways to promote these, and to champion the industry within domestic and international markets.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ann</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ex A – Summary of the UK Food Security Assessment 2010</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he 2010 UK Food Security Assessment represents the most current and complete analysis of the risks and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> challenges to UK food supply. A summary of each theme, and its assessment in 2010, follows:</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 59pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Glob</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">al availability</span></li></ol></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Headline indicator: Global food output per capita</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Global production of food relative to population is a fundamental in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dicator of global food security. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Global supply underpins UK availability and prices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Supply will need to meet growing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">global demand and deal with emerging climate challenges. Well-functioning markets are needed to spread these risks and send the right production and investment signals.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Current status: Green. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Assessment: F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ood supply has outgrown population, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">challenges ahead, including equitable distribution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ability of international and regional markets to bring supply and demand into line is a real strength, but it does not necessarily guarantee that everyone is fed or that natural resources are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sustainably used. For the medium term, the uncertain effects on the supply side of climate change and the challenges facing developing countries to increase production suggest an amber rating.</span></p><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 59pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Global resource </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sustainability</span></li></ol></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Headline indicator: Global land </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">use change</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Climate change is likely to create new stresses on natural resources. Food must be produced in a way that is environmentally sustainable or we will set up problems for the longer term.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Current status: Amber. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Assessment: It is unclear </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how much f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">orest loss </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ttributable to food production and that there has been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">small rise in farmland use since 1990s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. As</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the trend in the reduction of fore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">st areas is likely to continue, a red rating is given for the medium term. </span></p><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 59pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> UK availability of access</span></li></ol></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Headli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ne indicator: Diversity of UK supply</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sourcing nutritious food from a range of stable countries including domestically enhances security by spreading risks, widening options and keeping prices competitive. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Gateways into the UK are a key element of the UK’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> food infrastructure.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Current status: Green.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Assessment: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The UK‟s openness to trade has brought a very impressive diversity to UK food supply.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This openness ensures that UK food supply is very resilient to supply interruptions from specific countries and a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lso from within the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">while noting a critical dependency on our sea ports</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A green rating is given for the medium term. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="4" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="4" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 59pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> UK food chain resilience</span></li></ol></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Headline indicator: Energy dependency of UK food chain</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK food supply depends upon sophisticated and comple</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">x chain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and infrastructure, and is particularly dependent upon energy supplies in their various forms. Industry needs to manage a range of risks and disruptions to supply chain. Diversity is a key element of resilience, and also scale.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Current status: Amb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Assessment: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The domestic food chain is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a heavy user of energy but intensity is falling. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The surge in energy prices in 2007-8, and their continued </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uncertainty, can be expected to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increase the incentives to reduce energy intensity along with pressures for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> lower carbon production and distribution. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is expected that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> these favourable trends to continue into the future.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A green rating is given for the medium term.</span></p><ol start="5" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="5" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="5" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 59pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Household food security</span></li></ol></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Headline indicator: Low income households' share of spending on food</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Everyone should have the opportunity to ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cess and afford a healthy diet. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The aim of the headline indicator is to monitor the impact of price rises on the affordability of food, where affordability is measured by share of spending on food.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Current status: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Amber.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Assessment: Households’ share of spending on food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increased in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">008-9 because of inflation, but has remained relatively stable in the last few years and is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">expected to fall again once incomes recover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. A green rating is given for the medium term: res</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">umption of economic growth is expected, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">together with declining or stable real food prices, to result in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a declining share of spending on food.</span></p><ol start="6" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="6" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="6" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 59pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Safety and confidence</span></li></ol></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Headline indicator: Cases of food borne pathogens</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Public confidence in the UK food system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rests primarily on food safety. Assurance schemes seek to build this confidence. Consumer perceptions also matter.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Current status: Amber. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Assessment: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Campylobacter and salmonella</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cases have been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> down since 2000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> but listeria up. Reducing food-born</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e illne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ss is a top priority for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Food Standards Agency, so </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">future improvements are expected, with a green rating given for the medium term.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Annex B: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Russia case study</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ndustry could not access a valu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">able Russian market in beef and ruminant meat becau</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a thirty-year long ban imposed due to BSE. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Defra worked with British Embassy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Moscow and the Russian </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">remove this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ban. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This required sustained</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> pressure at official and political level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> over the last 30 years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accommodating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> inspection visits of UK plants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and completing relevant paperwork required by the Russian authorities in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cluding lengthy questionnaires. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This enabled trade to commence in ruminant meat after the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ban </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was lifted in December 2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further technical negotiation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s at Secretary of State and Chief  Veterinary Officer level in September this year extended the deal to offal, a priority for industry. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ndustry sources estimate that beef and lamb exports to Russia over the next three years could be worth up to £100 milli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on, making it a very lucrative market for UK industry. Negotiations are now being progressed for export of live sheep. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Page </span><span style="color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">33</span><span style="color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> of </span><span style="color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">33</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Alexandratos, N. and J. B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">ruinsma. 2012. World agriculture towards 2030/2050: the 2012 revision. ESA Working paper No. 12-03. Rome, FAO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">The Department has not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">made a stand-alone assessment of the UK’s food security as at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">.  Rather, this evidence paper cites the 2010 UK Food </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Security Assessment and offers commentary on relevant developments in policy since then</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Note: MFN i.e. the tariff applied to other WTO members who do not have preferential access to EU markets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> = Most favoured nation tariffs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">In the calculation of MFN </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">tariff averages, general tariffs (for non-WTO members) and non-MFN tariffs are included.   Source: Market Access Map, October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Source: Market Access Map, International Trade Centre NB: These are simple averages and not trade-weighted.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> OECD (2008) and EC (2013)</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/69565/pb13786-biofuels-food-security-120622.pdf</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">For example 0.3% p.a. for wheat and 0.5% p.a. for raw milk.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Foresight. The Future of Food and Farming</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> (2011)</span><span style="font